result.execSummary:
James William Miller was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means James William Miller was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 11:00 am - Defendant James William Miller appeared, in custody.  Mark T. Fuhr appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Comments by DA regarding waiver form. Court questions defendant regarding right to attorney. Exam by Court. Defendant waives right to attorney. Court examines defendant regarding waiver form and explains extradition procedure.  Defendant waives extradition. Court finds waiver to be free, knowing and voluntary and accepts. Adj. 11:07 am.

If not already completed DE must submit to booking at Sheriff's Dept prior to release. Defendant shall give written notice prior to any change in address or telephone number to the Clerk of this Court and Defense Attorney.

3:22 pm - Defendant James William Miller appeared, in custody.  Mark T. Fuhr appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Defendant has received a copy of complaint. Court notifies attorney of right to attorney. Exam by Court. No dispute that defendant is subject of complaint and is wanted by State of Missouri. DA states bond recommendation. No objection to bond recommendation. Comments by parties. Adj. 3:27 pm.
